    feat: Complete bare-metal STM32F411 port of Wolfenstein 3D engine
    
    Migrated the 2.5D raycasting engine from the SDL2 desktop simulator to
    a bare-metal ARM Cortex-M4 architecture (STM32F411CEU6 "BlackPill").
    
    Hardware & Pipeline Implementations:
    - Display: Built a double-buffered DMA SPI pipeline to upscale the 160x120
      8-bit internal framebuffer to 320x240 16-bit RGB565 for the ST7789 TFT.
    - Inputs: Implemented continuous DMA-driven ADC scanning for the analog
      joystick and 1ms SysTick shift-register debouncing for GPIO buttons.
    - Assets: Shrank Flash footprint from ~2.2MB to ~224KB by writing Python
      extractors to tightly pack only necessary E1M1 sprites and walls,
      utilizing Look-Up Tables (LUTs) in C to map virtual IDs to physical memory.
    - Clock Tree: Overclocked system from default 16MHz HSI to 96MHz via PLL,
      configured Flash wait states, boosted GPIO slew rates (OSPEEDR) to support
      48MHz SPI transmission, and scaled ADC prescalers for stability.
    - FPU: Enabled hardware floating-point coprocessors (CP10/CP11) to accelerate
      player rotation and raycaster trig math.
    
    The engine runs at a solid ~30 FPS with no underlying OS or HAL dependencies.

