    feat: Custom bare-metal STM32F411 engine port (Phase 1 - SDL2 Simulator)
    
    This commit marks the completion of the Phase 1 simulator for the STM32F411CEU6 Wolf3D port. The original id Software codebase has been entirely stripped, retaining only the map decompression logic. A custom, fixed-point 16.16 raycaster and rendering pipeline have been written from scratch to conform to strict MCU memory budgets (128KB SRAM, 512KB Flash).
    
    Core Engine Features:
    - Custom Fixed-Point Raycaster: Renders a 160x120 internal buffer (upscaled to 320x240) using 8-bit indexed textures and a 256-color RGB565 palette.
    - Orthogonal Sprite Rendering: Implemented mathematically correct camera-plane depth sorting to fix 2.5D sprite overlap, with near-plane clipping to prevent division-by-zero artifacts.
    - Advanced Bounding Box Physics: Independent X/Y movement decoupled from DDA, allowing the player and AI to slide smoothly along walls and objects without clipping.
    - Entity State Machines: Fully implemented AI states (Idle, Chase, Shoot, Die) with proper 4-frame staggered walk cycles and timer resets.
    - Zero-Allocation UI: Integrated a minimalist bottom-bar HUD utilizing a custom 3x5 bitmasked font (50 bytes) for real-time health and ammo tracking.
    - Asset Pipeline Fixes: Corrected the VSWAP.WL1 compiled-shape extraction logic to properly handle absolute Y-base pixel pointers, fixing vertical distortion on world sprites.
    
    The engine is currently stable in the SDL2 environment, with all E1M1 geometry traversable, sprite rendering accurate, and collision physics ratified.
    
    Next steps: Implementation of STM32 (SPI TFT driver, ADC joystick input).

